               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18411129-name-449" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18411129-name-449" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18411129-name-449" type="surname" value="PEARSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18411129-name-449" type="given" value="HANNAH"></interp>HANNAH PEARSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and live in Star-street, Padding<lb></lb>ton, the prisoner is my granddaughter, and lived with me—I let lodgings. On Saturday, the 5th of November, I missed a cloth cloak, which had been left to me by a gentleman who died three years ago—I had seen it safe about three days before—when the prisoner came home that evening I spoke to her about it—she said she knew, nothing about it—I asked her for the key of my drawer, and she threw it on the dresser at me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18411129-name-450" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18411129-name-450" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18411129-name-450" type="surname" value="HARRIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18411129-name-450" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS HARRIS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable D</hi> 14.) I was called in to the prosecutrix's house, and said to the prisoner, "You hear what your grand<lb></lb>mother charges you with "—she said, "May I be struck dead if I know any thing about it"—I took her to the station, and afterwards found the cloak in pledge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18411129-name-451" type="witnessName">
